# Tailwind CSS v4 — Hard Constraints

For configuration, theming, CVA, responsive, dark mode, and container query reference, use the `frontend-tailwind` skill.

## Never Construct Dynamic Class Names

Tailwind scans source files as plain text. Dynamically constructed class names are invisible to the compiler.

```tsx
// BAD
<div className={`bg-${color}-600`} />
<div className={`text-${error ? 'red' : 'green'}-600`} />

// GOOD
<div className={error ? 'text-red-600' : 'text-green-600'} />
```

Map dynamic props to a static lookup object:

```tsx
const COLOR_VARIANTS = {
  blue: 'bg-blue-100 text-blue-800',
  red: 'bg-red-100 text-red-800',
  green: 'bg-green-100 text-green-800',
} as const;

function Badge({ color }: { color: keyof typeof COLOR_VARIANTS }) {
  return <span className={COLOR_VARIANTS[color]} />;
}
```

## Never Use var() or Hex Colors in className

Use Tailwind semantic classes. Reserve `var()` for library props that do not accept `className`.

```tsx
// BAD
<div className="bg-[var(--color-primary)]" />
<div className="text-[#1e293b]" />

// GOOD
<div className="bg-primary" />
<div className="text-slate-800" />
```
